1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,180
 So now we're gonna take a look at what we do with Django

2
00:00:02,180 --> 00:00:06,800
 to handle logging users into and out of our application.

3
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:09,080
 So just, we talked about sessions recently

4
00:00:09,080 --> 00:00:12,320
 and making a session is not the same as being logged in.

5
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:15,400
 Logging in actually changes data in the session.

6
00:00:15,400 --> 00:00:18,760
 Logging in, in general, the most basic way of logging in

7
00:00:18,760 --> 00:00:20,960
 depends on the existence of a session

8
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:23,160
 and logging in is putting data into the session

9
00:00:23,160 --> 00:00:25,520
 about the current user and their name and their email

10
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:27,200
 and then logging out is removing it.

11
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:29,520
 In the session, you could have multiple users

12
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:30,920
 log in with one user, log out.

13
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:33,020
 Log in with a different user, log out.

14
00:00:33,020 --> 00:00:34,440
 If you're just in the same browser,

15
00:00:34,440 --> 00:00:35,940
 you're gonna end up with the same session

16
00:00:35,940 --> 00:00:37,640
 just associated with different users.

17
00:00:37,640 --> 00:00:41,380
 So remember, sessions and login are not the same thing.

18
00:00:41,380 --> 00:00:43,400
 Just like cookies and sessions are not the same thing,

19
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:45,440
 sessions and login are not the same thing.

20
00:00:45,440 --> 00:00:47,200
 But they all build on each other.

21
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:50,540
 Sessions build on cookies and login builds on sessions.

22
00:00:50,540 --> 00:00:53,560
 So to make this all work,

23
00:00:53,560 --> 00:00:55,360
 you have to add to your installed apps

24
00:00:55,360 --> 00:00:59,720
 all the Django support for all this login and log out stuff.

25
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:03,240
 Now if you automatically built your project

26
00:01:03,240 --> 00:01:04,680
 and you've got a settings.py

27
00:01:04,680 --> 00:01:06,900
 that they're gonna just put this in automatically.

28
00:01:06,900 --> 00:01:09,700
 So this is just so you know when you're looking at it

29
00:01:09,700 --> 00:01:12,580
 where it is that all this magic functionality comes from.

30
00:01:12,580 --> 00:01:14,740
 It comes from this installed apps.

31
00:01:14,740 --> 00:01:17,100
 Also for the login and log out,

32
00:01:17,100 --> 00:01:20,420
 you're gonna have to add a path to your project wide.

33
00:01:20,420 --> 00:01:24,000
 So dj4esamples, dj4esamples, urls.py.

34
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:25,680
 This is not in any of your applications.

35
00:01:25,680 --> 00:01:27,400
 This is in your Django project.

36
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:30,660
 And you add a path and there's a bunch of urls

37
00:01:30,660 --> 00:01:31,960
 and that gets all registered

38
00:01:31,960 --> 00:01:34,880
 and a whole bunch of wonderful magic happens at that point.

39
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:38,600
 And so that's how these urls are activated

40
00:01:38,600 --> 00:01:42,220
 in your Django project.

41
00:01:42,220 --> 00:01:43,940
 So the applications.

42
00:01:43,940 --> 00:01:48,940
 So the way we get the urls to the login and log out features

43
00:01:48,940 --> 00:01:51,580
 is we use the reverse.

44
00:01:51,580 --> 00:01:53,540
 We've been using reverse all along.

45
00:01:53,540 --> 00:01:57,780
 Reverse is the way we look up for a particular view.

46
00:01:57,780 --> 00:02:01,500
 And in some urls.py, matter of fact,

47
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:04,660
 in that Django contrib auth urls,

48
00:02:04,660 --> 00:02:06,940
 in that there is a name equals.

49
00:02:06,940 --> 00:02:09,020
 And so there's a view in there that they've got

50
00:02:09,020 --> 00:02:11,340
 that we didn't write and it has a name equals

51
00:02:11,340 --> 00:02:14,100
 and has name equals login and a name equals logout.

52
00:02:14,100 --> 00:02:16,080
 And so we can do a reverse lookup

53
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:19,140
 like we would have any of our views that we might have.

54
00:02:19,140 --> 00:02:23,220
 Say what is give me the url in this Django project

55
00:02:23,220 --> 00:02:27,360
 for the view named login or the view named logout.

56
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:28,200
 And it's pretty simple.

57
00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:29,860
 You could even probably hard code these

58
00:02:29,860 --> 00:02:33,260
 but maybe the route isn't exactly a count slash, right?

59
00:02:33,260 --> 00:02:35,520
 And so maybe you call them something else.

60
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:36,980
 And so that's why we use the reverse

61
00:02:36,980 --> 00:02:38,720
 to look these things up.

62
00:02:38,720 --> 00:02:42,520
 And so that's just a convenient way of doing it.

63
00:02:42,520 --> 00:02:45,820
 Now, one of the things about logging in

64
00:02:45,820 --> 00:02:48,360
 is sometimes you have an application

65
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:50,060
 and there's like a login button.

66
00:02:50,060 --> 00:02:51,620
 But sometimes you just have pages

67
00:02:51,620 --> 00:02:53,580
 that are protected by login.

68
00:02:53,580 --> 00:02:56,540
 And then when you go to a page,

69
00:02:56,540 --> 00:02:58,420
 it says, oh wait, you gotta log in first.

70
00:02:58,420 --> 00:02:59,640
 And then after you log in,

71
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:01,700
 you'll notice it typically just takes you right back

72
00:03:01,700 --> 00:03:03,560
 to the page that you want it to see.

73
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:07,100
 So you might bookmark a page when you're logged in

74
00:03:07,100 --> 00:03:09,440
 and then you log out and then you click

75
00:03:09,440 --> 00:03:10,540
 on that bookmark page.

76
00:03:10,540 --> 00:03:12,660
 But that requires that you be logged in.

77
00:03:12,660 --> 00:03:14,260
 So you're gonna go to the page.

78
00:03:14,260 --> 00:03:16,580
 And then when you're done logging in,

79
00:03:16,580 --> 00:03:18,180
 you wanna come right back to that page.

80
00:03:18,180 --> 00:03:20,360
 And so that's using redirecting.

81
00:03:20,360 --> 00:03:22,620
 But it's redirecting after login is successful

82
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:25,140
 or after logout is successful.

83
00:03:25,140 --> 00:03:26,820
 Logouts are almost always successful.

84
00:03:26,820 --> 00:03:28,460
 And so there's a parameter that we can add,

85
00:03:28,460 --> 00:03:30,020
 a gap parameter that we can add.

86
00:03:30,020 --> 00:03:31,220
 And it's the next equals.

87
00:03:31,220 --> 00:03:33,280
 And what we do is we give it a path.

88
